【English Version (Reference Only; Japanese Governs)】

This is a custom, platform-limited license. The Japanese text governs in case of conflict.

1. Permitted (within GitHub + private local use)
   (a) Personal use: viewing, local cloning, modification, local execution  
   (b) Educational use: classes, seminars, study groups  
   (c) No-Transfer Display  
       - Definition: transient in-person or limited screen-share viewing without transmitting source files, code text, recordings, or any persistent copy (including reconstructable full screenshot sets) to the viewer.  
       - After the display the viewer retains no persistent copy (file, recording, systematic screenshots).  
       - Sending code snippets in chat/email is not “No-Transfer Display” (see Section 4 for limited quotation).

2. GitHub Fork Tolerance
   Because the repository is public on GitHub, technical personal-evaluation forks may occur. Such forks (and activities within them limited to Section 1) are tolerated as an exception to the public redistribution ban in Section 3(2) provided that ALL of the following hold:  
   - No active promotion or broad advertising (e.g., repeated social media amplification, ranking submissions)  
   - No mirroring or reposting of the fork outside GitHub  
   - No commercial use  
   - This license notice remains intact  
   Breach of any condition removes the tolerance and constitutes a violation.

3. Prohibited
   (a) Commercial use  
       Definition: use whose primary intent or purpose is profit; resale; SaaS integration; continuous hosting aimed at monetization; providing the Software with advertising or sponsorship primarily for revenue. Incidental minimal ads (e.g., one small banner on a personal blog) are not treated as commercial use here.  
   (b) Public redistribution  
       Definition: making the code (in whole or substantial part) or derivative works available to the general public or a broad, unrestricted audience.  
       Examples: reposting to other source hosts (GitLab, Bitbucket, etc.); publishing to package registries (npm, PyPI, etc.); app store publication; posting the full code on websites/blogs; mass excerpt sharing on social networks; posting to public or secret/unlisted gists or paste services.  
       Personal evaluation forks meeting Section 2 conditions are excepted.  
   (c) Distribution of derivative works beyond the permitted scope (Sections 1 & 2)  
   (d) Removing or altering copyright or this license text  
   (e) Large-scale automated redistribution / systematic scraping publication  
   (f) Serving the Software (in whole or substantial part) via GitHub Pages or other hosting features to the general public  
   (g) Providing any means for third parties to retain a copy (in whole or substantial part) beyond No-Transfer Display (e.g., sending files/archives, gists/paste postings, recording/stream archives, bulk copy/paste, systematic screenshot sets, persistent cloud links) except for tolerated forks under Section 2

4. Limited Quotation
   Up to 10 lines per instance for commentary/review/academic citation with attribution (author + repository URL). Combining multiple excerpts to reconstruct the whole or a substantial part is prohibited.  
   Reference: “Substantial part” may contextually include more than 10% of total lines or any portion exceeding 50 lines.

5. External Reposting
   Reposting (in whole or substantial part) — including tolerated fork contents — to other public hosting platforms, package registries, archives, paste services, or public/secret/unlisted gists is prohibited. Private local storage for your own use (without enabling third-party access) is not “reposting.”

6. Disclaimer (NO WARRANTY)
   THE SOFTWARE IS PROVIDED “AS IS”, WITHOUT WARRANTY OF ANY KIND, EXPRESS OR IMPLIED, INCLUDING BUT NOT LIMITED TO THE WARRANTIES OF MERCHANTABILITY, FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE AND NON-INFRINGEMENT. IN NO EVENT SHALL THE AUTHOR BE LIABLE FOR ANY CLAIM, DAMAGES OR OTHER LIABILITY, WHETHER IN AN ACTION OF CONTRACT, TORT OR OTHERWISE, ARISING FROM, OUT OF OR IN CONNECTION WITH THE SOFTWARE OR THE USE OR OTHER DEALINGS IN THE SOFTWARE.

7. Governing Language
   The Japanese version controls in case of inconsistency.

8. Future (Re)Licensing
   The author may adopt for future versions a more permissive open-source license (e.g., MIT) or introduce dual-licensing. Versions distributed prior to such change remain under the terms in effect at the time of their distribution unless the author explicitly declares that the new (more permissive) terms also apply retroactively.

9. Enforcement
   Upon confirmed violations the author may issue remediation or takedown requests or pursue other reasonable actions.

